# Slice 4.1 Design Review & Implementation Blueprint

I read every file you named plus the boot/priv path, the kernel-call trace path, the CI/release workflows, and the `.cargo` config. Your framing is ~90% correct; I found **three material errors** and several smaller gotchas. I'll flag the errors inline (marked **CORRECTION**) and answer all seven points concretely.

---

## CORRECTIONS to your framing (read these first)

**CORRECTION 1 — the `[ksys]` trace will NOT fire for VM's boot whoami.** This is the biggest one and it directly invalidates the hint in requirement 6. In `kernel/src/system/mod.rs:122-130`, the `[ksys N]` line is gated **only** on `n % KCALL_TRACE_EVERY == 0` (every 100th kernel call). There is **no** head-trace (`TRACE_HEAD`) on the kernel-call path — that only exists on the `[ipc]` path (`kernel/src/ipc/mod.rs:70,114`). VM's single SYS_GETINFO at boot is one of the first handful of kernel calls; it will almost certainly land on a non-multiple-of-100 and produce **no `[ksys]` line at all**. So "a NEW `[ksys]` dispatch from caller=7" is the wrong thing to grep for. The observable proof is on the **`[ipc]` head trace** instead — see requirement 6 below.

**CORRECTION 2 — stub C's whoami is also NOT visible as a `[ksys]` line for the same reason.** Your phrase "stub C SYS_GETINFO [ksys caller=13]" assumes `[ksys]` head-traces stub C. It doesn't; stub C is a *tight SENDREC-to-SYSTEM loop* (`user_stub.S` C does GET_WHOAMI repeatedly), so it's stub C that eventually *drives* `CALL_COUNT` to multiples of 100 — meaning the `[ksys 100] caller=13 call=0 result=0` lines you see are stub C's *steady-state* loop, not its first call. VM's boot whoami is a single call buried in that stream and won't get its own `[ksys]` line. (It *will* appear on the `[ipc]` head trace; see below.)

**CORRECTION 3 — "ping = NOTIFY from RS" cannot be distinguished from any other NOTIFY by m_type alone, and in real MINIX SEF the RS heartbeat is more subtle.** Your classify predicate (`m_type==NOTIFY_MESSAGE && m_source==RS endpoint`) is *implementable and correct for this slice*, but be aware: `build_notify_message` (`kernel/src/ipc/notify.rs:41-47`) zeroes the entire payload and sets only `m_type=NOTIFY_MESSAGE`. So **every** NOTIFY — from RS, from HARDWARE/IRQ, from CLOCK, from any server — arrives with identical `m_type=NOTIFY_MESSAGE` and is disambiguated *only* by `m_source`. Your RS-source check is the right discriminator. Just don't expect a payload-carried "ping" subtype; there's no room for one in a notify. (Minor: in real MINIX the SEF ping is `is_notify(m_type) && who==RS`; you're faithful.)

Everything else in your framing checks out: SRV_T = `!0` (`proc/flags.rs:124`) so VM already has NOTIFY(4) and SENDNB(5) trap bits and full `ipc_to`/`k_call_mask` (`proc/table.rs:372-376`); the SENDREC-to-SYSTEM fast path is synchronous and never blocks (`ipc/mod.rs:176-180`, `system/mod.rs:68-133`); `Message` is `Copy` but has **no** `Default`/constructor (built via struct literal everywhere); `OK == 0`; the build.rs rerun list omits server-rt (`build.rs:95-100`).

